<topic id="json-schema-components">
  <title>JSON Schema Components</title>
  <prolog>
    <metadata>
      <keywords>
        <indexterm>JSON Schema diagram editor<indexterm>Components</indexterm></indexterm>
        <indexterm>JSON Schema Design mode<indexterm>Components</indexterm></indexterm>
      </keywords>
    </metadata>
  </prolog>
  <body>
    <p id="p_b5b_cgk_54b">A schema diagram contains a series of interconnected components. To
      quickly identify the relation between two connected components, the connection is represented
        as:<ul id="ul_c5b_cgk_54b">
        <li id="li_d5b_cgk_54b">
          <p id="p_e5b_cgk_54b">A thick line to identify a connection with a required component (in
            the following image, <xmlelement>family</xmlelement> is a required element).</p>
          <p id="p_f5b_cgk_54b">
            <fig id="fig_g5b_cgk_54b">
              <title>Example: Required Component</title>
              <image href="../img/JSONSchema_required_component.png"/>
            </fig>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li id="li_h5b_cgk_54b">
          <p id="p_i5b_cgk_54b">A thin line to identify a connection with an optional component (in
            the following image, <xmlelement>email</xmlelement> is an optional element).</p>
          <p id="p_j5b_cgk_54b">
            <fig id="fig_k5b_cgk_54b">
              <title>Example: Optional Component</title>
              <image href="../img/JSONSchema_optional_component.png"/>
            </fig>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul></p>
  </body>
